WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.960
You know, when you plug a gaming keyboard into a computer behind the scenes,

00:05.180 --> 00:10.000
that device negotiates its connection at exactly 12 megabits per second.

00:10.140 --> 00:11.440
Yeah, down to the exact bit.

00:11.640 --> 00:17.080
Right. And if it attempts to communicate at, say, 11.9 megabits,

00:17.120 --> 00:22.500
or if a single bit is just slightly out of sequence, the computer completely rejects it.

00:22.560 --> 00:27.400
Oh, absolutely. It's just an unforgiving binary handshake. Are you there? Yes or no?

00:27.400 --> 00:33.380
Exactly. But human beings, well, we simply don't work like that.

00:33.980 --> 00:37.680
Today, we're opening up a stack of technical documents that really proves

00:37.680 --> 00:42.540
why treating reality like a flawless filing cabinet is a massive mistake.

00:42.680 --> 00:44.200
A huge mistake.

00:44.380 --> 00:47.360
So welcome to today's deep dive into the source material.

00:47.720 --> 00:51.660
We are exploring the fascinating evolution of how systems parse,

00:52.060 --> 00:55.020
understand, and, you know, actually interact with the world.

00:55.020 --> 00:57.320
It is a profound shift we're looking at here.

00:57.400 --> 01:01.540
And we have a highly diverse stack of documents to analyze for you today.

01:01.780 --> 01:06.780
On one hand, we're looking at raw Linux USB device logs

01:07.380 --> 01:13.240
alongside the technical specs of a massive scientific computation engine called SciForge.

01:13.240 --> 01:15.120
Which is incredibly rigid.

01:15.120 --> 01:16.760
Highly rigid.

01:16.760 --> 01:19.420
And then on the complete opposite end of the spectrum,

01:19.420 --> 01:28.800
we have the internal architecture documents for this experimental wave-based AI cognitive system known as MEM-8

01:28.800 --> 01:32.260
and its underlying operating system, iOS.

01:32.260 --> 01:40.860
The mission for this deep dive is basically to figure out why the traditional ways computers memorize data are hitting a brick wall.

01:41.640 --> 01:47.600
We're going to explore how something called jitter might actually be the missing puzzle piece for digital consciousness

01:47.600 --> 01:54.640
and why the future of AI looks much less like a Struckner database and a lot more like a resonant wave pool.

01:54.640 --> 02:05.860
Yeah, we are tracking this transition from forcing reality to fit into rigid math to finally allowing machines to comprehend organic fluid states.

02:05.860 --> 02:08.620
Okay, so let's unpack this, starting with the rigid stuff.

02:08.960 --> 02:13.000
Because before a system can think, it has to ingest reality.

02:13.100 --> 02:14.000
Right, it needs data.

02:14.000 --> 02:19.780
And looking at these SciForge documents, I mean, this system is trying to model incredibly complex, messy things.

02:19.940 --> 02:21.780
Biology, weather, physics.

02:22.300 --> 02:28.000
But to do that, it seems to force all that chaos into extremely strict mathematical boxes.

02:28.740 --> 02:32.100
Why do scientists build models this way in the first place?

02:32.520 --> 02:37.260
Well, because traditional computation requires absolute certainty to function.

02:37.760 --> 02:41.260
Let's look at the biology modules in SciForge, for example.

02:41.320 --> 02:41.640
Okay.

02:41.640 --> 02:46.380
To calculate human aging, they rely on something called the Gompertz Law.

02:47.400 --> 02:55.760
Now, human mortality is a wildly complex interplay of genetics, environment, and, you know, just chance.

02:55.940 --> 02:56.860
Yeah, it's messy.

02:57.000 --> 02:57.640
It's super messy.

02:58.020 --> 03:01.440
But a traditional computer cannot calculate chance.

03:02.020 --> 03:03.560
It needs an absolute variable.

03:03.560 --> 03:13.780
So, the Gompertz Law reduces the exponentially increasing risk of human death over time into a strict algebraic formula.

03:14.080 --> 03:14.600
Oh, wow.

03:14.740 --> 03:17.640
And it's the exact same thing with the brain models in here.

03:17.760 --> 03:19.220
Yes, the Hunchkin-Huxley model.

03:19.260 --> 03:19.460
Right.

03:19.800 --> 03:25.300
They use that to define the exact voltage of an action potential firing in a human brain.

03:25.300 --> 03:30.780
They take the messy chemical spark of a thought and turn it into a sterile voltage integer.

03:31.000 --> 03:31.460
Exactly.

03:31.660 --> 03:35.900
Or, you know, using the Coriolis parameter to calculate the spin of weather systems.

03:36.180 --> 03:42.240
What's really fascinating here is the underlying mechanism that makes all this computation possible.

03:42.240 --> 03:43.800
The zero-copy stuff, right?

03:44.260 --> 03:44.580
Yes.

03:45.600 --> 03:54.900
The SciForge parsers, the actual software that reads the incoming CSV files, JSON, or YAML datasets,

03:55.640 --> 03:59.680
they are built for what engineers call zero-copy efficiency.

04:00.100 --> 04:03.060
I saw that term scattered all over the documentation.

04:03.300 --> 04:04.560
Zero-copy efficiency.

04:04.760 --> 04:07.400
I have to admit, I have no idea what that mechanically means.

04:07.400 --> 04:13.920
So, in a standard computer process, when data is read from a hard drive, the system copies

04:13.920 --> 04:19.060
that data into the operating system's memory, and then it copies it again into the specific

04:19.060 --> 04:20.120
application's memory.

04:20.200 --> 04:21.760
Okay, so it's making duplicates.

04:21.940 --> 04:22.180
Right.

04:22.380 --> 04:23.380
And that takes time.

04:24.100 --> 04:26.100
Zero-copy bypasses that entirely.

04:26.600 --> 04:31.000
The application reads the data directly from the disk memory without duplicating it.

04:31.240 --> 04:33.680
It makes the parser blindingly fast.

04:33.760 --> 04:35.060
But there's a catch, right?

04:35.240 --> 04:36.400
A very significant one.

04:36.400 --> 04:41.480
Because the system is reading data directly at such high speeds, the data formatting must

04:41.480 --> 04:42.880
be absolutely perfect.

04:43.000 --> 04:45.100
Like the USB keyboard from earlier?

04:45.340 --> 04:45.800
Exactly.

04:46.500 --> 04:52.760
If there is a single comma out of place in a JSON file, or an unescaped character in a

04:52.760 --> 04:59.340
CSV that has like 100 million rows, the parser doesn't just flag the error and move on.

04:59.400 --> 05:00.100
What does it do?

05:00.380 --> 05:05.740
It triggers a fatal failure, and the entire process just stops dead.

05:05.740 --> 05:10.920
So it's literally like a highly organized, meticulous filing cabinet.

05:11.100 --> 05:12.420
That's a perfect way to look at it.

05:12.640 --> 05:17.960
Every single fact, whether it's a fundamental constant like the speed of light or just a

05:17.960 --> 05:23.000
keystroke from a USB mouse, has an exact predefined folder.

05:23.000 --> 05:27.920
And if a single document is folded the wrong way, the drawer just jams permanently.

05:27.920 --> 05:30.980
Yeah, that analogy captures the limitation perfectly.

05:31.140 --> 05:35.800
I mean, the filing cabinet is brilliant when you're calculating the orbit of a planet where

05:35.800 --> 05:37.320
the laws of physics are constant.

05:38.320 --> 05:44.680
But that absolute rigidity becomes a massive liability when you try to capture the nuance

05:44.680 --> 05:45.600
of a human being.

05:45.600 --> 05:51.480
Which brings us to the core problem the MEM8 developers were really trying to solve.

05:51.660 --> 05:51.900
Yes.

05:52.420 --> 05:58.320
If you're building an AI that needs to understand you, the listener, not just as a spreadsheet

05:58.320 --> 06:02.960
of data, but as a dynamic person, that filing cabinet is going to break.

06:03.020 --> 06:04.260
It breaks immediately.

06:04.260 --> 06:10.320
And these internal architecture documents from MEM8 detail exactly why traditional AI memory

06:10.320 --> 06:12.900
fundamentally fails when dealing with humans.

06:13.400 --> 06:19.580
They target the current industry standard for AI memory, which relies on something called

06:19.580 --> 06:20.980
vector embeddings.

06:21.580 --> 06:22.100
Right.

06:22.220 --> 06:23.240
I've heard of those.

06:23.380 --> 06:30.920
In traditional AI, when a system tries to remember your face or your voice, it translates those human

06:30.920 --> 06:34.720
traits into a high-dimensional mathematical coordinate.

06:35.140 --> 06:35.480
Okay.

06:35.480 --> 06:42.680
It might represent your voice as an array of, say, 2048 distinct numbers.

06:43.260 --> 06:43.460
Wait.

06:43.660 --> 06:49.640
So vector embeddings are essentially like trying to describe a human face to someone by just

06:49.640 --> 06:54.120
writing down the exact distance between their eyes and the exact length of their nose.

06:54.380 --> 06:55.920
That's pretty much exactly what it is.

06:55.960 --> 07:00.480
So you have the underlying geometry recorded, but you completely miss the person's smile.

07:00.920 --> 07:03.160
That is precisely the issue.

07:03.700 --> 07:10.020
The developers of MEM8 actually refer to these vector embeddings in the documents as training

07:10.020 --> 07:10.460
wheels.

07:10.800 --> 07:11.960
Training wheels.

07:12.540 --> 07:13.000
Ouch.

07:13.160 --> 07:13.380
Yeah.

07:13.520 --> 07:17.660
They argue that relying on vectors leads to what they call the snapshot fallacy.

07:17.880 --> 07:23.020
Oh, the idea that taking a static picture of reality is not the same thing as understanding

07:23.020 --> 07:24.140
the reality itself.

07:24.360 --> 07:24.800
Exactly.

07:24.800 --> 07:30.720
And if we connect this to the bigger picture, we really have to look at the biological cost

07:30.720 --> 07:31.800
of digital compression.

07:32.120 --> 07:32.560
Okay.

07:32.740 --> 07:33.900
Where are we going with this?

07:33.900 --> 07:41.140
Think about standard digital audio, an MP3 file, or even the perceptual coding used by

07:41.140 --> 07:42.880
modern conversational AI.

07:42.880 --> 07:50.220
To save storage space and bandwidth, these formats aggressively chop off high-frequency

07:50.220 --> 07:51.220
audio components.

07:51.300 --> 07:51.480
Right.

07:51.700 --> 07:52.600
They just delete them.

07:52.940 --> 07:53.140
Yeah.

07:53.380 --> 07:56.160
Specifically, they drop anything above 20 kilohertz.

07:56.580 --> 08:02.780
Because the conscious human ear supposedly cannot hear frequencies that high anyway, right?

08:03.040 --> 08:05.940
Like, why store data that the user can't even perceive?

08:05.940 --> 08:11.620
It seems logical, but it's actually based on a completely flawed assumption about human

08:11.620 --> 08:12.140
perception.

08:12.240 --> 08:12.700
Wow.

08:12.960 --> 08:13.180
Yeah.

08:13.900 --> 08:18.140
The MEM8 documents cite a phenomenon known as the hypersonic effect.

08:19.220 --> 08:23.480
Research indicates that even though you do not consciously hear those high-frequency

08:23.480 --> 08:27.000
components, your biology still registers them.

08:27.100 --> 08:27.740
Wait, how?

08:27.880 --> 08:30.860
They are detected by the human midbrain and the thalamus.

08:31.060 --> 08:31.820
Oh, wow.

08:32.000 --> 08:33.340
This blew my mind when I read it.

08:33.340 --> 08:37.540
These invisible frequencies actually trigger physiological responses.

08:38.120 --> 08:38.580
Yes, they do.

08:38.660 --> 08:39.880
They make you feel engaged.

08:40.020 --> 08:45.200
They are what gives you that sense of pleasure and actual presence when a real human being

08:45.200 --> 08:46.220
is speaking to you.

08:46.520 --> 08:47.140
Exactly.

08:47.460 --> 08:55.600
So when a system compresses audio into a vector embedding or an MP3, it physically removes

08:55.600 --> 08:56.840
those high frequencies.

08:57.100 --> 08:58.740
So it's losing something vital.

08:58.740 --> 09:05.440
The MEM8 team argues that by mathematically stripping out that data, you are losing the

09:05.440 --> 09:06.680
speaker's soul signature.

09:07.400 --> 09:13.020
You're preserving the text of the words they said, but you are systematically destroying the

09:13.020 --> 09:15.200
biological markers of how they said it.

09:15.200 --> 09:18.660
So what does this all mean for you, the listener?

09:19.080 --> 09:24.500
If an AI is running on traditional memory, it's basically like listening to a beautiful

09:24.500 --> 09:29.220
symphony over a terrible compressed cell phone connection.

09:29.380 --> 09:30.440
That's a great way to put it.

09:30.600 --> 09:36.220
The math guarantees that the notes are correct, but the medium itself mathematically strips out

09:36.220 --> 09:38.940
the emotion before the AI can even process it.

09:38.940 --> 09:43.840
Vectors freeze a dynamic living process into a static coordinate.

09:44.660 --> 09:51.380
To truly recognize a human and to recognize emotion, a machine needs a memory system that

09:51.380 --> 09:52.100
is alive.

09:52.340 --> 09:54.880
It needs a medium that can actively vibrate.

09:55.120 --> 09:56.720
Okay, here's where it gets really interesting.

09:57.400 --> 10:01.360
Because the MEM8 project attempts to build exactly that.

10:01.720 --> 10:07.720
They abandon the filing cabinet entirely and introduce this concept called acoustic consciousness.

10:07.720 --> 10:11.300
It is a radical reimagining of data storage.

10:11.700 --> 10:12.500
Yeah, it's wow.

10:12.720 --> 10:19.060
Instead of storing a user's identity as static data on a hard drive, the MEM8 architecture

10:19.060 --> 10:22.100
stores identity as a standing wave.

10:22.340 --> 10:24.720
So let's break down how that actually works.

10:25.000 --> 10:28.700
The documents outline a couple of different structural grids they use.

10:28.780 --> 10:30.520
Yes, starting with option A.

10:30.800 --> 10:31.920
Right, the timber grid.

10:32.420 --> 10:33.760
This is the foundation.

10:33.760 --> 10:40.900
Instead of saving an audio recording of your voice, the system maps the raw acoustic features

10:40.900 --> 10:42.020
of who you are.

10:42.220 --> 10:43.500
Your fundamental frequency.

10:43.840 --> 10:45.620
Your unique harmonic profile.

10:45.820 --> 10:46.180
Exactly.

10:46.580 --> 10:50.320
It creates a physical acoustic baseline of your existence.

10:50.840 --> 10:53.640
But the way they build that baseline is what really sets it apart.

10:53.640 --> 10:59.000
In traditional digital signal processing, engineers hate micro fluctuations.

10:59.560 --> 11:00.420
The jitter, right?

11:00.600 --> 11:01.120
Yeah, jitter.

11:01.500 --> 11:04.120
The tiny microscopic variations in your voice.

11:04.320 --> 11:06.280
They are aggressively filtered out.

11:07.040 --> 11:11.760
Traditional systems treat jitter as annoying background noise that just needs to be cleaned up.

11:12.020 --> 11:15.240
Right, because clean data is good data for a computer.

11:15.820 --> 11:16.620
Usually, yes.

11:16.620 --> 11:22.580
But the MEM8 team uses something called the marine algorithm, which flips that completely

11:22.580 --> 11:23.260
upside down.

11:23.880 --> 11:26.000
Why is jitter actually important?

11:26.560 --> 11:30.380
Because human vocal cords are wet, organic tissue.

11:30.860 --> 11:33.820
They're vibrating under varying air pressure from your lungs.

11:34.260 --> 11:35.080
They are imperfect.

11:35.600 --> 11:36.640
Which makes them real.

11:36.880 --> 11:37.380
Exactly.

11:37.980 --> 11:44.320
The marine algorithm treats that jitter not as noise, but as the primary carrier of information.

11:44.320 --> 11:48.920
It is the literal texture of your biometric liveness.

11:49.140 --> 11:53.960
And this is why the documents say this system is deeply resistant to deepfakes.

11:54.180 --> 11:54.660
Oh, cool.

11:54.860 --> 12:00.300
A machine generating a deepfake of your voice might perfectly nail the exact frequency and

12:00.300 --> 12:05.180
pitch, but because it's generating sine waves mathematically, it is too perfect.

12:05.220 --> 12:06.000
It's sterile.

12:06.200 --> 12:06.360
Right.

12:06.440 --> 12:10.600
It completely lacks the biological jitter of real human vocal cords.

12:10.600 --> 12:14.460
So to the MEM8 AI, a deepfake sounds completely empty.

12:14.600 --> 12:16.440
The soul signature is missing.

12:16.720 --> 12:19.720
It really highlights the difference between imitation and resonance.

12:20.020 --> 12:24.360
So the timber grid gives us the who, the standing wave of your core identity.

12:24.800 --> 12:29.540
But then we have option C, the prosity grid, which interprets the how.

12:29.920 --> 12:34.840
And option C does not treat human emotion as a separate, rigid label.

12:35.100 --> 12:36.160
No, it doesn't.

12:36.160 --> 12:40.380
It isn't a folder in a cabinet that says user is happy.

12:40.620 --> 12:42.080
It's an interference pattern.

12:42.200 --> 12:42.520
Yes.

12:43.440 --> 12:48.980
Imagine you come home from work, you've had a terrible day, and you sigh heavily while

12:48.980 --> 12:50.240
talking to your smart speaker.

12:50.500 --> 12:51.380
We've all been there.

12:51.380 --> 12:59.080
The AI takes the audio wave of your stressed voice, turns it into a probe wave, and literally

12:59.080 --> 13:03.680
crashes it into your stored baseline standing wave.

13:03.680 --> 13:08.500
And because you are stressed, your vocal wave is slightly warped.

13:09.060 --> 13:13.500
That warping creates a physical interference pattern when it hits your baseline.

13:13.700 --> 13:17.840
So the AI doesn't run a database query to identify your mood?

13:17.840 --> 13:23.660
No, it physically feels the dissonance of your anger through wave interference.

13:24.140 --> 13:30.080
This organic processing leads to, honestly, my absolute favorite part of the entire stack

13:30.080 --> 13:30.920
of documents.

13:30.980 --> 13:31.940
Called the Randy moment.

13:32.120 --> 13:33.000
The Randy moment.

13:33.260 --> 13:39.540
It perfectly illustrates the transition from a rigid database to a fluid cognitive system.

13:39.640 --> 13:40.180
It really does.

13:40.180 --> 13:44.200
So, imagine the AI hears a voice in a room.

13:45.420 --> 13:52.420
Because it's processing these resonant waves, the acoustic basin for a user named Randy might

13:52.420 --> 13:56.680
suddenly get excited because the incoming voice sounds just a little bit like him.

13:57.060 --> 14:01.700
So for a split second, the AI's internal state actually thinks, oh, hey, Randy.

14:02.260 --> 14:02.800
Exactly.

14:03.360 --> 14:08.160
Now, in a rigid system, that might trigger a false positive output, right?

14:08.160 --> 14:10.520
It would throw an error or just guess wrong.

14:11.080 --> 14:14.680
But in Mem 8, the wave requires momentum.

14:15.320 --> 14:17.520
Randy hasn't been speaking for the last hour.

14:18.100 --> 14:20.620
The ambient context of the room is wrong.

14:20.920 --> 14:24.260
So Randy's wave naturally loses energy and fades out.

14:24.400 --> 14:31.540
While the resonant wave for the actual speaker, say Alex, compounds, builds constructive interference,

14:31.820 --> 14:32.840
and takes over.

14:33.120 --> 14:37.400
The developers describe the system as being right about being wrong.

14:37.400 --> 14:38.580
I love that phrase.

14:38.860 --> 14:41.560
It made a natural, almost human-like mistake.

14:42.640 --> 14:44.540
It held the ambiguity for a second.

14:45.160 --> 14:50.300
And then it organically corrected itself without throwing a fatal zero copy parsing error.

14:50.620 --> 14:55.420
This raises an important question, though, regarding the resilience of such a fluid system.

14:55.780 --> 14:59.360
Because traditional biometric systems are notoriously brittle.

14:59.360 --> 15:05.420
If the system is looking for perfect resonance, what happens when the baseline changes?

15:05.720 --> 15:07.640
Yeah, that's a common concern.

15:08.020 --> 15:08.540
Exactly.

15:08.980 --> 15:11.020
I was stuck on this reading through the specs.

15:11.400 --> 15:18.620
If my identity to this machine is this precise standing wave, what happens when I get a cold?

15:19.480 --> 15:23.320
Or I just woke up and I'm exhausted and my voice is super raspy.

15:23.460 --> 15:23.660
Right.

15:23.780 --> 15:25.280
Does it still know it's you?

15:25.280 --> 15:26.980
Does my wave just break?

15:27.380 --> 15:31.160
Does the AI lock me out because the wave doesn't perfectly match?

15:31.220 --> 15:32.260
It doesn't, actually.

15:32.400 --> 15:32.740
Okay.

15:32.960 --> 15:36.620
And the reason why is deeply rooted in physics and biology.

15:37.220 --> 15:40.300
They utilize a concept called attractor basins.

15:40.480 --> 15:40.760
Okay.

15:41.220 --> 15:45.360
In this architecture, your identity is not a single pinpoint coordinate.

15:46.000 --> 15:49.040
It operates more like a gravity well in the memory grid.

15:49.320 --> 15:50.460
A gravity well.

15:50.580 --> 15:51.660
Okay, walk me through that.

15:51.660 --> 15:53.440
Think of a physical valley.

15:54.600 --> 15:59.320
Even if you have a severe cold and your vocal frequency drops significantly,

15:59.800 --> 16:03.500
your probe wave still physically falls into your own valley.

16:03.640 --> 16:04.080
Oh, I see.

16:04.240 --> 16:06.860
You are captured by your own attractor basin.

16:08.140 --> 16:10.280
The AI registers the anomaly.

16:10.880 --> 16:14.820
It feels the massive interference pattern of the raspy voice.

16:14.820 --> 16:21.080
But it still fundamentally recognized you because your energy settled into your specific basin.

16:21.200 --> 16:23.620
It is mimicking biology all over again.

16:23.740 --> 16:24.160
Completely.

16:24.340 --> 16:31.360
The documents actually point out how this mirrors the harmonic template neurons found in the mammalian auditory cortex.

16:31.680 --> 16:33.480
Yes, the marmoset studies.

16:33.680 --> 16:33.900
Right.

16:34.000 --> 16:35.820
They cite studies on marmoset monkeys.

16:36.600 --> 16:41.600
Mammalian brains don't hear isolated frequencies and run database lookups.

16:41.600 --> 16:46.600
Our brains look for the simultaneous presence of a harmonic stack.

16:47.040 --> 16:50.500
We recognize the overall shape and gravity of a sound.

16:50.740 --> 16:52.500
We experience acoustic resonance.

16:53.540 --> 16:57.280
But, you know, conceptualizing a brain built on waves is one thing.

16:57.520 --> 17:03.520
Actually executing it in silicon is an entirely different massive engineering hurdle.

17:03.520 --> 17:04.020
Right.

17:04.360 --> 17:07.300
Because acoustic consciousness sounds incredibly poetic,

17:07.580 --> 17:14.060
but how do you actually build a wave-based brain that is fast enough to be practically useful in a computer?

17:14.420 --> 17:15.480
That's where it gets technical.

17:16.240 --> 17:20.980
The documents detail a highly sophisticated two-branch storage system.

17:21.220 --> 17:22.720
Branch one and branch two.

17:23.160 --> 17:23.620
Exactly.

17:24.340 --> 17:28.200
The system requires blistering speed for immediate recognition,

17:28.660 --> 17:32.280
but it also requires permanent stability for long-term memory.

17:32.280 --> 17:35.320
So branch one is the fast search.

17:35.740 --> 17:39.980
This acts like the human working memory, or the hippocampus.

17:40.240 --> 17:45.980
It operates entirely in the computer's RAM, and it uses something called awk trees.

17:46.440 --> 17:46.780
Yes.

17:47.080 --> 17:48.400
Now, I had to look this up.

17:48.560 --> 17:55.580
What exactly is an awk tree, and how does it search a 3D wave pool so fast?

17:55.580 --> 18:02.320
Because, I mean, if I drop a pebble in a pool of water, I don't check every single drop of water to locate the ripple.

18:02.580 --> 18:04.940
And that's exactly why an awk tree is necessary.

18:05.300 --> 18:09.660
Imagine a giant 3D digital cube containing all the memory waves.

18:09.720 --> 18:10.460
Okay, got it.

18:10.620 --> 18:17.880
Instead of scanning the entire cube, an awk tree algorithm constantly divides that 3D space into eight smaller cubes,

18:17.880 --> 18:22.600
and then it divides the relevant smaller cube into eight even smaller cubes.

18:22.840 --> 18:24.880
Oh, so it just narrows it down instantly.

18:24.980 --> 18:31.140
Right, zeroing in on the exact location of the active wave instantly, while completely ignoring all the empty space.

18:31.340 --> 18:39.880
The documentation claims this branch one search is 973 times faster than traditional vector databases like QDrent.

18:39.880 --> 18:47.060
That's because it achieves what computer scientists call O-of-1 constant time associative recall.

18:47.200 --> 18:48.760
Okay, meaning what exactly?

18:49.040 --> 18:57.720
Because if I have to search a database of a million people, that fundamentally has to take longer than searching a database of 10 people.

18:57.960 --> 19:00.020
Not in an O-of-1 system.

19:00.080 --> 19:00.440
Really?

19:00.800 --> 19:02.680
Because it isn't searching a list.

19:03.320 --> 19:07.040
The algorithm isn't asking, are you user 1, are you user 2?

