19:50.920 --> 20:07.280
If you have a complex 3D wave rippling in RAM, but a standard hard drive just writes data sequentially in a flat, one-dimensional line, how do you smash a 3D wave flat without completely destroying it?

20:07.280 --> 20:09.880
It's a brilliant engineering solution, honestly.

20:09.880 --> 20:15.560
They map the 3D space using a mathematical algorithm known as a Hilbert curve.

20:16.100 --> 20:17.080
Okay, I love this part.

20:17.080 --> 20:23.480
So to save a multidimensional thought to a flat disk, they essentially use a Hilbert curve to unfold it.

20:23.560 --> 20:23.980
Exactly.

20:23.980 --> 20:41.020
It sounds like trying to unfold a highly complex 3D origami swan into a single perfectly straight line of paper, save it to the disk, and then somehow fold it instantly back into the exact same 3D swan the second the AI needs to remember it.

20:41.020 --> 20:48.360
That is actually a phenomenal way to visualize it. The Hilbert curve is a continuous fractal space-filling curve.

20:48.500 --> 20:49.280
Fractal, right.

20:49.300 --> 20:56.920
Its primary mathematical magic is that it maps multidimensional space into one dimension while preserving spatial locality.

20:57.040 --> 21:01.520
Meaning things that were close together in 3D stay close together in 1D.

21:01.880 --> 21:02.360
Exactly.

21:02.360 --> 21:15.020
If two memories or two acoustic features were interacting closely in the 3D wave pool, the Hilbert curve guarantees they are written physically close to each other on the 1D hard drive track.

21:15.100 --> 21:17.020
Oh, so it doesn't have to search everywhere.

21:17.300 --> 21:31.140
Right. So when the AI needs to recall a specific memory, the hard drive can read the entire neighborhood of related concepts in one quick physical pass, rather than the drive headhunting all over the disk.

21:31.140 --> 21:34.380
It is just a staggering level of engineering.

